OLLI reported 2Q adj. EPS of \(\) 0.99\(above Street\) \ \(0.92\) ) comprised of \(+5.0\%\) same- store sales or a \(10.8\%\) 2- year stack \((> \text{Street at} +1.7\%)\) and gross margin expansion of \(+206\) bps Y/Y to \(39.9\%\) (above Street at \(39.1\%\) ) translating to \(21\%\) gross profit dollar growth (doubling the model's \(\sim 10\%\) TTM average). Looking ahead, management raised the FY25 EPS outlook to \(\) 3.76- 3.84\((\text{vs.}\) \ \(3.65 - 3.75\) prior and Street \(\) 3.76\(based on +3.0 - 3.5\%\(SSS (vs + 1.4 - 2.2\%\) prior),85 net new stores ( = 15% unit growth vs. 75 prior), gross margin - 40.3% ( > historical algo / vs. prior - 40.0%), and 11.2% margin at the midpoint (vs 11.0 - 11.2% prior guide and Street at 11.2%).

Near term, we see a strong closeout deal backdrop, an improving competitive backdrop, and consistent execution supporting same- store sales growth. Multi- year, we see annual "organic" unit growth acceleration to double digits in FY26+ (with 10 years to 1,300 store saturation) translating to a \(\sim 13\%\) compounding EPS growth story on low- single- digit same- store sales with lateral consolidation representing incremental potential wallet- driven same- store sales and unit growth upside not in our model (with no structural constraint to prepandemic \(13 - 14\%\) unit growth for a multi- year period). We rate OLLI Overweight.
Our Dec '26 price target of \(\) 159\(is based on \sim 32.5x our FY27E EPS of\) \ \(4.95\) ( \(=\) linear regression multiple for '26/27 profile).

Model Implications: We model FY25 EPS of \(\) 3.88\(vs. Street\) \ \(3.76\) and FY26 EPS of \(\) 4.42\(vs. Street\) \ \(4.30\) . Importantly, putting together our upside 2H25 same- store sales growth of mid single digits and 2H25 merchandise margin expansion opportunity, our math points to upside FY25E EPS of \(\sim\) 4+ (vs. management's guidance of \(\) 3.76- 3.84\$ . Remain Overweight with \(\) 159\(Dec'26 price target (with historical mid 30' multiple =\) \ \(175\) equity value).

- Balance Sheet Snapshot: OLLI exited 2Q with \(\) 460.3M\(of cash and short-term investments with no borrowings on its\) \ \(100M\) revolving credit facility. OLLI exited 2Q with inventory \(+19.9\%\) Y/Y (vs. 1Q \(+16\%\) ). During 2Q, OLLI repurchased \(\) 12M\(of shares and has\)\\(304M\) of remaining capacity under its current share repurchase program. On stores, OLLI opened 29 new stores in 2Q - representing \(+16.8\%\) unit growth Y/Y - ending the quarter with 613 stores across 32 states. For FY25, management now expects 85 new store openings vs. 75 prior \((= +15.2\%\) unit growth Y/Y) and capex of \(\) 83-88M\(vs FY24's\) \ \(121M\) , primarily for new stores/remodeling existing stores.

Near term, we see a strong closeout deal backdrop, an improving competitive backdrop, and consistent execution supporting same- store- sales growth. Multi- year, we see annual "organic" unit growth acceleration to double digits in FY26+ (with 10 years to 1,300 store saturation) translating to a \(\sim 13\%\) compounding EPS growth story on low- single- digit same- store sales with lateral consolidation representing incremental potential wallet- driven same- store sales and unit growth upside not in our model (with no structural constraint to pre- pandemic 13- 14% unit growth for a multi- year period). We rate OLLI Overweight.
Our Dec '26 price target of \(\) 159\(is based on \~32.5x our FY27E EPS of\) \ \(4.95\) ( \(= \text{linear}\) regression multiple for '26/27 profile).
